    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-02-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-02-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="314"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d314">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/3020</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sammons</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Minister in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Reinsch</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="19" xml:id="d314fn19">Copy forwarded to the Department by
                        the Consul General under covering letter of same date; received Apr.
                        1.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-02-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 21, 1919</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 2687</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to record that the Internal
                    Peace Conference of China opened here, on yesterday, in the former German Club,
                    the delegations being as follows— <list>
                        <item>
                            <hi rend="italic">For the North:</hi> Chu Chi-chien, Wu Ting-chang, Wang
                            Ko-ming, Sze Yu, Fan Chu, Wang Yu-ling, Liu Un-kou, Li Kuo-tseng, Kiang
                            Shao-chi, and Hsu Fu-su.</item>
                        <item>
                            <hi rend="italic">For the South:</hi> Tong Shao-yi, Tsang Chi-chao, Hu
                            Han-ming Mao Chia-so, Tseng Yen, Kuo Tsung-sung, Liu Kuang-lieh, Wang
                            Pah-chung, Peng Yung-yi, Yao Ming-luan, and Li Shi-yin.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>The initial session opened at 9:00 o’clock in the morning, and it is proposed to
                    adhere to early morning activities during future sessions.</p>
                <p>Further, as a matter of record, there is enclosed herewith the speeches made by
                    the chief delegates for the North and for the South, and other data relative to
                    the conference, the same having appeared in today’s issue of the <hi
                        rend="italic">Shanghai Times</hi>
                    <note n="20" xml:id="d314fn20">Enclosure not printed.</note> (accepted as being
                    pro-Japanese in its policies). This newspaper’s account of the opening session
                    is more connected and more convenient for filing, as a matter of record, than
                    the accounts appearing in the other newspapers.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Thomas Sammons</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
